This post contains sensitive content: Were there slaves in Litchfield? Did you know that in 1790, there were reportedly 26 people enslaved in Litchfield? We often think of the south when we think about slavery, but the north also enslaved people. Two little girls were enslaved on North Street. Candace and Elvira (‚ÄúVira‚Äù) were gifted to Julius and Dorthoy Deming for their wedding from Dorothy‚Äôs father, Henry Champion. At just five-years-old, they had to leave everything and everyone they had ever known behind and make the journey from Colchester to Litchfield, following their new owners. When they were 22-years-old, they ran away. The ad pictured was placed in the newspaper in order to help encourage their capture and return. More is written and known about Vira than Candace, as she was frequently mentioned in the Demings‚Äô letters throughout the years. Surprisingly, she remained friendly with the Demings and was emancipated in 1801, around the age of 25. The Litchfield Historical Society has a letter that she wrote to Dorothy Deming in 1802, in which she talks about fashion, inquires about the new members of congress, and offers to send lobster and oranges to the Deming children. The Deming-Perkins Memorial Family History states that Vira went on to open a restaurant named ‚ÄòElvira‚Äôs‚Äô, which was reportedly joined to the Park Theater in New York City. You can learn more about Vira at the Litchfield Historical Society. In the African American experience there are countless tales of overcoming horrific pain and suffering while working to preserve human dignity. This story, sadly, is a part of our community‚Äôs history. Our intent is to always speak up and educate. We in no way agree with nor support the treatment of human beings in such a manner. Litchfield Magazine will strive to get the conversation right. We are committed to talking about important issues and to learning and growing with our readers. By The History Chix @history_chix Photo Credit: Litchfield Historical Society @litchfieldhistory #litchfieldcounty #litchfieldhills #nwct #ctvisit #litchfieldct #thehistorychix #litchfieldhistoricalsociety

bell hooks was an author, professor, feminist, and social activist whose work focused on examining and uplifting the works of other Black writers while helping provide academic theory to support political organizing happening on the ground. Her extensive catalogue of written works and academic lectures covered topics such as race, class, gender, art, history, sexuality, mass media, and feminism. Some of her most well-known books being ‚ÄúAin‚Äôt I a Woman: Black Women and Feminism‚Äù and ‚ÄúFeminism is for Everybody‚Äù which are now considered standard texts in intersectional feminist circles. We are beyond thankful for her constructive critiques and contributions to the feminist movement and know that we would be remise if we didn‚Äôt uplift her legacy during #BlackHerstoryMonth.

Several months after taking office, President Biden raised refugee admissions to 62,500 for the remainder of Fiscal Year 2021. According to Refugee Council USA's report, the U.S. only resettled 11,411 refugees. That's just 18% of the annual goal and the lowest number ever in our country's history. As we enter the new year, we must continue to rebuild and support people seeking a better life in the U.S. The refugee admissions goal for FY2022 is 125,000, and we must hold the administration accountable for resettling as many refugees as possible and restore our nation's legacy of welcome.

TIME TO PUT SOME POWER BEHIND THE GREEN The Environmental Justice Summit is a bold platform for representation and activism that elevates and amplifies the voices and power of people of color as leaders in the environmental justice space. Environmentalism is a movement that impacts all classes, colors, and demographics of society, yet there is a lack of diversity within the movement itself. People of color are strong supporters of environmental issues. Which makes sense as communities of color have a much higher risk of getting polluted and have historically been targeted as dumping sites for toxic waste. The 6th Annual Environmental Justice Summit will bring together leading BIPOC environmental organizers from the Bay Area and beyond. We will come together to share experiences and discuss steps to diversify the Green Movement and the needs of our most vulnerable communities. Today, we commemorate the liberation of the Auschwitz concentration camp and honor the 6 million lives lost in the Holocaust. This is also a day to remember the survivors, including 15-year-old Rachel Genuth. Rachel had endured the horror of Auschwitz, and in the final years of World War II was moved to Bergen-Belsen. As Rachel continued to fight for her life, unknowingly by her side was Brigadier H. L. Glyn Hughes. Hughes commitment to helping as many prisoners as possible is what saved Rachel's life. Rachel went on to be the mother of Bernice Lerner, author of "All the Horrors of War." Lerner's book is the first book to pair the story of a Holocaust victim with that of a liberator. Find out more here: http://ow.ly/YMi450HkwHF:=:https://jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu/title/all-horrors-war

January is National Slavery and Human Trafficking Prevention Month in the United States (previously referred to as National Human Trafficking Awareness Month). The Defense Department defines human trafficking as a crime in which force, fraud or coercion is used to compel a person to perform labor, services or commercial sex. In 2019, Polaris, who runs the National Human Trafficking Hotline, identified 22,326 victims and survivors along with 4,384 traffickers in the US. ‚Ä¢ Learn more: https://polarisproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Polaris-2019-US-National-Human-Trafficking-Hotline-Data-Report.pdf ‚Ä¢ #JLBetterTogether #JuniorLeague #jlm #jlmonroe

What You Need to Know... But Won't Hear on the News Reproductive Racism: Margaret Sanger, Eugenicist Founder of Planned Parenthood was a known racist who wanted to exterminate the Black population and others she deemed unfit to live. Sanger, herself, said about her <Negro Project>, "We do not want word to go out that we want to exterminate the Negro population and the minister is the man who can straighten out the idea, if it ever occurs to any of their more rebellious members." Sanger's mission was, also, to put Black doctors and nurses in charge of birth control clinics to reduce any mistrust of a racist health care system... and to gain the trust of the Black community. It seems her project is working... because more Black babies are aborted than any other race? Ask yourself... Why?... What's, Really, Going On? FYI: Eugenics is the theory that society can be improved through planned breeding. It goes, even, deeper than racism, because the philosophy espouses it has "THE RIGHT" to determine who should live, who should reproduce... and who should die. Information You Should Know #BlackLove

Trans Day of Visibility (TDOV) is an annual awareness day observed on March 31st. The day is dedicated to celebrating the accomplishments and lives of transgender and gender nonconforming people while raising awareness of the work that still needs to be done to achieve trans justice and liberation. The Trans Health Program at the LGBTQ Center Long Beach is currently accepting submissions for this year's Trans Day of Visibility Community Spotlight Video! This video will be a community collaboration focusing on our varying experiences under the theme of "Trans Joy". The trans and gender-diverse community is often asked to share their challenges and experiences to people who do not identify as trans. We find it important that we share a wide range of voices, identities, and celebrations. We would like to create an opportunity to discuss what visibility means from a positive, trans-centered perspective. If you know anyone who would like to share their experience with the community, please have them contact us at TransHealthLB@centerlb.org with the subject "TDOV Video 2022". We will send them a list of question prompts and instructions for video submission. Thank you, and we are excited to see who will participate this year!

Black History Month 2022 Caribbean people, notably Afro Caribbean individuals in the black equity movements, have long been a part of shaping the United States' social and intellectual advancement. This year, the Virgin Islands Department of Education's Division of Virgin Islands Cultural Education is honoring eleven Afro Caribbean individuals who shaped the political and social environment of the United States. Arturo A Schomburg and Nella Larsen both have close ties to the Virgin Islands, having their parents originate in the Danish West Indies, also known as the Virgin Islands of the United States. Arturo A. Schomburg founded the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture, a research library within the New York Public Library with a collection of over 11 million items. Additionally, Nella Larsen's works were recently resurrected in the black-and-white drama film Passing, which was released in 2021. The film is based on Nella Larsen's 1929 novel of the same name, and the title refers to African-Americans whose skin tone was light enough to be recognized as white, a condition known as "passing." The Division will include biographies of the following Caribbean activists, writers, entertainers, and visual artists throughout the month: Kwame Ture/Stokley Carmichael, Arturo A. Schomburg, Nella Larsen, Sidney Poitier, Marcus Garvey, Amanda Seales, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Lin-Manuel Miranda, Grandmaster Flash, Edwidge Dandicat, and Roxanee Gay are all featured in the 2022 series.

During #BlackHistoryMonth, Team TFSS is taking some moments to highlight some very important Black TGNC icons who have been influential within the LGBTQ+ community! This week's spotlight is on Kye Allums, a former college basketball player who bravely and openly came out as a transgender man in 2010. Since then, Kye has involved himself in supporting the community as a transgender advocate, public speaker, artist, and mentor to LGBT youth. By sharing openly sharing his story, Kye showed other trans and gender non-conforming youth that they are not alone in their journey, and certainly not the only ones with a trans experience. We believe that public figures sharing their experiences with identity, such as Kye did, can be valuable and instrumental in constructing a society that is accepting of all, regardless of identity or expression.

Prison gerrymandering turns inequities in our criminal justice system into representational inequities. These communities of color are incarcerated at disproportionate rates nationwide. In 2019, 56 percent of the United States‚Äô prison population was Black or Latino, despite these groups making up only 32 percent of the overall population. Prison gerrymandering turns disparities in incarceration into disparities in representation; electoral maps do not reflect the true size of the largely Black and Latino urban communities. For example, according to the Texas Civil Rights Project, Harris County (containing the city of Houston) and Dallas County would likely have received an additional state house seat each if incarcerated people were counted at their homes. While these inequities have long existed, they have become magnified with the rise of mass incarceration starting in the 1970s.

February is #BlackHistoryMonth and this year to celebrate, the Minnesota Council on Disability will feature Black historical figures and leaders with disabilities. After all, Black history is Disability history! Today we feature Fannie Lou Hamer, civil rights activist, organizer, and Black disabled woman! Visit MCD‚Äôs website for a list of people featured so far: https://www.disability.state.mn.us/events/black-disabled-history-month/ Image description: A background of black, red, yellow, and green stripes with text that reads "#BlackDisabledHistory, Fannie Lou Hamer was born in 1917 and was the youngest of 20 siblings. Passionate about Black liberation, Hammer is recognized as a civil rights activist who fought for African Americans to vote. In addition to living with the effects of Polio, Hammer had kidney damage, a blood clot, and a limp due to being beaten in jail. Hamer advocated for women in politics and helped form the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party in 1964. Hamer died in 1977 but her legacy and contributions continue to inspire future generations. To the right of the text is a black and white image of Hamer, wearing a dress and speaking into a hand-held microphone.

BLACK HISTORY MONTH PROFILE: ROOSEVELT LEGGETT Roosevelt Leggett, who has been on staff at Limestone for almost three years serving as the Junior Database Administrator for the Information Technology Department, is a graduate of the University of South Carolina Upstate with a bachelor's degree in information management and systems. He also worked in the USC-Upstate IT Department. After graduating, he initially went full-time into Christian ministry at USC-Upstate. After a few years of working with the ministry, he realized how much he enjoyed being on college campuses and how much he missed working in IT. And that led him to Limestone. He is currently pursuing his master‚Äôs degree in health informatics at Limestone. Leggett resides in Spartanburg, where he can often be found riding his bike downtown, enjoying coffee from Little River coffee shop, and exploring the area every chance he can get. He and his wife, Hilary, are parents to their 16-month-old daughter and they are expecting their second child to be born next month. "February is a month where we get to talk about the accomplishments and successes of black people in America,‚Äù he said about the importance of Black History Month. ‚ÄúThose are stories that often go untold. There's been a lot of pain in the lives of African-Americans, and through that pain, a lot of joy has come." A recent inspiration of his within the black community is author, Isabel Wilkerson. Her book, ‚ÄúThe Warmth of Other Suns: The Epic Story of America's Great Migration,‚Äù gave Leggett a better understanding of the impact that the Great Migration had on American history. It tells the story of black southerners migrating from the south ‚Äì which still heavily oppressed the black community ‚Äì to the north in search of better treatment and opportunities. However, they were still met with animosity throughout the country. Through perseverance and hard work, they were able to change the trajectory of America for the better. He encourages everyone to pick up a copy to read for themselves. William Raveis Real Estate is proud to be the sponsor of Asian Treasures from the Billings Collection! Nantucket Historical Association The exhibition draws from the collection that longtime Nantucket residents and world travelers David Billings and Beverly Hall Billings have assembled over 50 years. It all started with a book, and two pieces of Asian art David Billings received as a gift, and now their collection includes 4,000 artifacts. Most pieces included in the show are being shown for the first time publicly, and the NHA is excited to be able to give islanders and visitors the opportunity to see a significant portion of the collection. The exhibition will feature paintings, textiles, bronzes, and jade items. However, ceramics will predominate, including some of the earliest known pieces of earthenware from 5,000 BCE and porcelain, which dates from the Qing Dynasty, the last Imperial Chinese Dynasty. Book your visit now on NHA.org for opening day on Friday, May 27! #AsianTreasures #HappeningonNantucket #MemorialDayWeekendNantucket #NantucketWhalingMuseum #WilliamRaveisNantucket #theBillingscollection #QingDynasty #ImperialChineseDynasty #5000BCE
